			array( 'q' => 'Do I have to drain the pool for tile work?', 'a' => 'Yes, the water level needs to drop below the work line. We coordinate the partial drain so you are not down a full pool of water for any longer than necessary.' ),
			array( 'q' => 'Glass vs porcelain tile?', 'a' => 'Glass tile delivers depth and color shift in sun, costs about 1.6x more than porcelain, and demands precise grout work. Porcelain is the workhorse: durable, cost-effective, and 95 percent of the visual impact.' ),
			array( 'q' => 'Can you match the existing tile?', 'a' => 'Sometimes. We carry samples from major manufacturers and do a free in-person color match. If your tile is older than 10 years, an exact match is unlikely; we recommend a deliberate contrast instead.' ),
			array( 'q' => 'How long does tile and coping replacement take?', 'a' => 'A standard waterline tile and coping refresh runs 1 to 3 weeks depending on scope and whether custom mosaic accents are included. Combining it with a full plaster remodel extends the timeline since the shell work happens first.' ),
			array( 'q' => 'What coping material holds up best in Los Angeles heat?', 'a' => 'Travertine and precast concrete both perform well; travertine stays cooler underfoot in direct sun, which matters on exposed decks. Bullnose brick and cast stone are common budget-friendly alternatives that hold up nearly as well.' ),
			array( 'q' => 'Do you repair cracked or lifting coping without a full replacement?', 'a' => 'Small sections can sometimes be repaired or reset in place if the coping material is still in good condition and the issue is isolated. Widespread cracking usually points to a settling or freeze-related issue underneath that repair alone will not fix.' ),
			array( 'q' => 'Can the deck be resurfaced without touching the tile or coping?', 'a' => 'Yes, deck refresh is offered independently. Options include a resurfacing overlay on existing concrete, new pavers, or a stone veneer, all installed without disturbing the pool shell or waterline.' ),
			array( 'q' => 'What is a mosaic accent and does it cost a lot more?', 'a' => 'A mosaic accent is a small decorative glass or stone tile feature, usually on steps, a sun shelf, or a feature wall. It adds a moderate premium over standard waterline tile since the installation is more labor-intensive, but it is typically a few hundred to low thousands depending on size.' ),
			array( 'q' => 'Will new tile and coping increase my home value?', 'a' => 'Pool finish work is one of the higher-return backyard improvements in Los Angeles, especially in neighborhoods where buyers expect a well-kept pool. It will not single-handedly move an appraisal, but it removes a common objection during a sale.' ),
